entry.title: Fix flaky test ShellSurfacePresentationTimeRecorderTest.RecorderDestroyedBeforePresent.
entry.content:
Why is the previous code flaky (with AutoNeedsBeginFrame

feature enabled)?

The root_surface submits two frames in this test case. If

both frames are submitted before the first DrawAndSwap, the

test will pass. Because frame 2 activation at the viz side

will discard frame 1, which will send back presentation

feedback for frame 1. And then DrawAndSwap will cause

presentation feedback for frame 2.

On the other hand, if a DrawAndSwap happens between frame 1

and frame 2, it will cause presentation feedback for frame

1. Later frame 2 arrives. Since it has no damage, the next

DrawAndSwap decides that it doesn't need to draw, which also

means it won't trigger presentation feedback. The feedback

could be triggered by the next frame submission, but in this

test there isn't a third frame.



Why is the previous code *not* flaky, if AutoNeedsBeginFrame

is disabled (while ReactiveFrameSubmission enabled)?

That is because without AutoNeedsBeginFrame, there won't be

unsolicited frame submission. Instead, it needs to wait for

BeginFrame to submit. Without running a RunLoop to receive

BeginFrame events, frame 1 will be discarded at the Exo side

directly when frame 2 is submitted.

entry.title: Reland "Validate that imported functions exist on oldest Windows version"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit c2c0b1c9df8c56c6e3010a8b71268b805d6e2e7f



ASAN builds pull in syncapi functions via an apiset definition but

these are not directly exported by a dll so do not appear in the

dumped exports from our specimen Windows 10 system. Docs[0] for these

functions suggest they are available in Windows 8+ so we add an entry

to the allowed modules list for asan builds only. This allows the

test to alert us if unexpected new imports are added to the asan

(or regular) build in future.



generate_allowed_imports.py used to output the full variable

declaration for kAvailableImports but now only exports a list

of {module, {function, function}}, ...



[0] https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-waitonaddress



Original change's description:

> Validate that imported functions exist on oldest Windows version

>

> Chromium supports Windows versions back to 10.0.10240. If a new

> non-delayloaded import is added to chrome.exe, chrome_elf.dll or

> chrome.dll and that function isn't exported by the related system

> dll on Windows 10240 then chrome will not load.

>

> This CL adds new tests to the delayloads_unittests target that

> take the required imports for the above modules and validate that

> they are listed as exports on a specimen Windows 10.0.10240

> system.

>

> To allow for upgrades in future we generate the C++ structure

> needed as import from the output of the dumpbin /exports command.

>

entry.title: Reland "[reland] tflite/mediapipe/eigen: avoid exposing flags to disable warnings"
entry.content:
This reverts commit c3098c68481bfbe7eb5738944f80823ac80b7500.



Reason for revert: There was a patch that landed at the same time that had an unused function, that was reverted too.



Original change's description:

> Revert "[reland] tflite/mediapipe/eigen: avoid exposing flags to disable warnings"

>

> This reverts commit 911d6a41bf156229df40499196ff4a4065beb4cd.

>

> Reason for revert: Breaks compile due to new warnings:

>

> ../../components/omnibox/browser/actions/history_clusters_action.cc:64:5: error: unused function 'TransformKeywordScoreForUma' [-Werror,-Wunused-function]

> 64 | int TransformKeywordScoreForUma(float keyword_score) {

> | ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

> 1 error generated.

>

> Original change's description:

> > [reland] tflite/mediapipe/eigen: avoid exposing flags to disable warnings

> >

> > This patch is exactly the same as the first. It was reverted because

> > of some code not checking a return value of a function marked as

> > [[nodiscard]].

> >

> > eigen's config contains a handful of flags that disable warnings.

> > tflite was depending on this config via a public_config, which

> > means any code using tflite was inheriting a bunch of flags that

> > disable warnings. This is risky, and not something we should do.

> >

> > This patch splits eigen's config into two. The one that tflite

> > depends upon via public_config does not disable any warnings. This

> > means code using tflite no longer disables a bunch of compiler

> > warnings. As a result of this I needed to add some flags to disable

> > warnings in other code that was picking up the flags from eigen.

> > That this code needs to disable warnings is not new, it was masked

> > by eigen's config.

> >

> > This also adds -Wno-unused-function to tflite as this was masked

> > by flags from eigen. Without it the following error is generated:

> >

> > ../../third_party/tflite/src/tensorflow/lite/kernels/internal/optimized/neon_tensor_utils.cc:587:13: error: unused function 'DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate' [-Werror,-Wunused-function]

entry.title: [reland] tflite/mediapipe/eigen: avoid exposing flags to disable warnings
entry.content:
This patch is exactly the same as the first. It was reverted because

of some code not checking a return value of a function marked as

[[nodiscard]].



eigen's config contains a handful of flags that disable warnings.

tflite was depending on this config via a public_config, which

means any code using tflite was inheriting a bunch of flags that

disable warnings. This is risky, and not something we should do.



This patch splits eigen's config into two. The one that tflite

depends upon via public_config does not disable any warnings. This

means code using tflite no longer disables a bunch of compiler

warnings. As a result of this I needed to add some flags to disable

warnings in other code that was picking up the flags from eigen.

That this code needs to disable warnings is not new, it was masked

by eigen's config.

by flags from eigen. Without it the following error is generated:



../../third_party/tflite/src/tensorflow/lite/kernels/internal/optimized/neon_tensor_utils.cc:587:13: error: unused function 'DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate' [-Werror,-Wunused-function]

entry.title: viz: Allow registering a pending HostFrameSinkClient
entry.content:
Currently Viz allows only 1 HostFrameSinkClient to be bound to a

FrameSinkId for the lifetime of this ID. This client maps to the

RenderWidgetHostView for FrameSinkIds associated with a renderer side

compositor.



In order to reuse the compositor for a cross-RenderFrame navigation in

the renderer process, ownership of the FrameSinkId needs to be

transferred between RenderWidgetHostViews.



This change adds an API to register a HostFrameSinkClient in pending

state. This will be used by a speculative RenderWidgetHostView to claim

ownership of the FrameSinkId when the previous RenderWidgetHostView is

destroyed.



The model still allows only 1 HostFrameSinkClient to be registered at

a time. Since this API is only used for same-process cross-RFH

navigations, the old RenderWidgetHostView is guaranteed to be destroyed

before the new RenderWidgetHostView is made visible.

entry.title: [TLSAA][RWS] Fix rSAFor browsertest race condition
entry.content:
It looks like https://crrev.com/c/4150994 accidentally omitted the

expiration from one of the settings that ought to be intentionally-

expired in the ThirdPartyGrantsExpireOverIPC test.



This meant that there was a race between the IPC from the browser

process, and the IPC sent manually by the test; if the browser process

won, then the network service would end up having a non-expired grant,

and the test would pass (because the test's expectation was incorrect,

I think). If the test's IPC won, then the browser process's IPC would

override the network service's grants, and would cause the test to

fail.



Apparently, the inclusion of field trial configs changes the browser's

behaviors enough to affect the outcome of this race, so the test fails

if we run it with field trials enabled.



This CL fixes the missing expiration, and also removes the race

altogether by skipping the update of the browser's

HostContentSettingsMap. It also removes some unnecessary navigations

during test setup.
